## 2026-04-07 17:45 — DEC-002 — XDC GT lane DP label corrections

**Decision**: The XDC `##` annotations for 10 GT lines (6 unique DP lanes,
P and N each) had wrong DP numbers relative to the VITA 57.1 HPC standard.
Comments corrected; `set_property` directives NOT changed.

Affected ports and corrections:

| XDC Port | FMC Pin | Old DP label (wrong) | New DP label (correct) |
|---|---|---|---|
| rx_data_p[1] | A06 | DP0_M2C_P | **DP2_M2C_P** |
| rx_data_n[1] | A07 | DP0_M2C_N | **DP2_M2C_N** |
| rx_data_p[2] | C06 | DP2_M2C_P | **DP0_M2C_P** |
| rx_data_n[2] | C07 | DP2_M2C_N | **DP0_M2C_N** |
| tx_data_p[0] | A22 | DP0_C2M_P | **DP1_C2M_P** |
| tx_data_n[0] | A23 | DP0_C2M_N | **DP1_C2M_N** |
| tx_data_p[1] | A26 | DP1_C2M_P | **DP2_C2M_P** |
| tx_data_n[1] | A27 | DP1_C2M_N | **DP2_C2M_N** |
| tx_data_p[2] | C02 | DP2_C2M_P | **DP0_C2M_P** |
| tx_data_n[2] | C03 | DP2_C2M_N | **DP0_C2M_N** |

**Source**: ANSI/VITA 57.1-2008 standard, Section "Signal Definitions for
high-pin count connector" (page 48 of the standard). Cross-verified against
Xilinx AC701 User Manual Appendix B and HiTechGlobal FMC module datasheet.
The standard defines:
- DP0: C2/C3 (C2M), C6/C7 (M2C)
- DP1: A22/A23 (C2M), A2/A3 (M2C)
- DP2: A26/A27 (C2M), A6/A7 (M2C)
- DP3: A30/A31 (C2M), A10/A11 (M2C)

The FMC_HPC_ADRV9009 library symbol, the `ADRV9009 FMC Signals` tab of
the pin mapping spreadsheet, and the Sheet 3 global labels ALL agree with
the VITA 57.1 standard. Only the XDC comments were wrong.

**Rationale**: The pin mapping spreadsheet Tab 1 was hand-verified by Ravv
in March 2026 and matches VITA 57.1 exactly. Sheet 3's FMC labels were
generated from the spreadsheet. The library was built to match the
spreadsheet. Only the XDC comments have the error, indicating the author
of the XDC comments got the DP labels confused with the logical lane
ordering (rx_data[0]→DP1, rx_data[1]→DP2, etc.) when writing the
`##` annotations.

**Bitstream impact**: NONE. The `set_property PACKAGE_PIN` directives in
the XDC reference FPGA balls (C4/C3/D2/D1/B2/B1/A4/A3/D6/D5/C8/C7/B6/B5/A8/A7
for data lanes), which are correct. Vivado builds from ball names, not from
comments. The bitstream physically drives the right carrier pins.

